chapter:
Deploying &productname; on &gke-full; (GKE)
yes
&readmefirst;
&productname; supports deployment on &gke-full; (GKE). This chapter describes the steps to prepare a &productname; deployment on GKE using its integrated network load balancers. See
for more information on GKE.
Prerequisites
The following are required to deploy and use &productname; on GKE:
A Google Cloud Platform (GCP) user account or a service account with the following IAM roles. If you do not have an account, visit to create one.
compute.admin. For details regarding this role, refer to .
container.admin. For details regarding this role, refer to .
iam.serviceAccountUser. For details regarding this role, refer to .
Access to a GCP project with the &kube; Engine API enabled. If a project needs to be created, refer to . To enable access to the API, refer to .
gcloud, the primary command line interface to Google Cloud Platform. See for more information and installation instructions.
&cfcli-prereq; &kubectl-prereq; &jq-prereq; &curl-prereq; &sed-prereq;
&min-deploy-note;
Creating a GKE cluster
In order to deploy &productname;, create a cluster that:
Is a Zonal or Regional type. Do not use a Alpha cluster.
Uses Ubuntu as the host operating system. If using the gcloud CLI, include --image-type=UBUNTU during the cluster creation.
Allows access to all Cloud APIs (in order for storage to work correctly).
Has at least 3 nodes of machine type n1-standard-4. If using the gcloud CLI, include --machine-type=n1-standard-4 and --num-nodes=3 during the cluster creation. For details, see .
Has at least &node_size; GB local storage per node.
(Optional) Uses preemptible nodes to keep costs low. For details, see .
Set a name for your cluster:
&prompt.user;export CLUSTER_NAME="cap"
Set the zone for your cluster:
&prompt.user;export CLUSTER_ZONE="us-west1-a"
Set the number of nodes for your cluster:
&prompt.user;export NODE_COUNT=3
Create the cluster:
&prompt.user;gcloud container clusters create ${CLUSTER_NAME} \ --image-type=UBUNTU \ --machine-type=n1-standard-4 \ --zone ${CLUSTER_ZONE} \ --num-nodes=$NODE_COUNT \ --no-enable-basic-auth \ --no-issue-client-certificate \ --no-enable-autoupgrade
Specify the --no-enable-basic-auth and --no-issue-client-certificate flags so that kubectl does not use basic or client certificate authentication, but uses OAuth Bearer Tokens instead. Configure the flags to suit your desired authentication mechanism.
Specify --no-enable-autoupgrade to disable automatic upgrades.
Disable legacy metadata server endpoints using --metadata disable-legacy-endpoints=true as a best practice as indicated in .
Get kubeconfig File
Get the kubeconfig file for your cluster.
&prompt.user;gcloud container clusters get-credentials --zone ${CLUSTER_ZONE:?required} ${CLUSTER_NAME:?required} --project example-project
